# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alipur-sign-language
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alipur-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] For over a decade, the deaf children of the village have attended a boarding school in Mampong-Akuapem, where the ASL based Ghanaian Sign Language is used.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] As a consequence, this language has become the first language of these children and their command of AdaSL is decreasing.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] This is likely to lead to a complete shift of the deaf community in Adamorobe to Ghanaian Sign Language.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] As such, AdaSL is an endangered sign language.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Adamorobe is situated approximately 30 to 40 kilometers north of Accra in the Akuapem Hills.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] It is a predominantly Akan village, with the majority of the population speaking the Akan language (Akuapem Twi) in addition to using AdaSL.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] The community gained attention for its unusually high incidence of hereditary deafness, a phenomenon that has shaped the village's cultural and linguistic landscape.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Unlike many other deaf communities where deaf individuals are socially marginalized, Adamorobe's deaf residents are fully integrated into village life.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Hearing villagers commonly use AdaSL in daily interactions, creating a bilingual environment that bridges the hearing and deaf worlds seamlessly.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] AdaSL shares signs and prosodic features with some other sign languages in the region, such as Bura Sign Language, but it has been suggested these similarities are due to culturally shared gestures rather than a genetic relationship.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] AdaSL has features that set it apart from the sign languages of large deaf communities studied so far, including the absence of the type of classifier construction that expresses motion or location (sometimes called "entity classifiers").
[src:alipur-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Instead, AdaSL uses several types of serial verb constructions also found in the surrounding spoken language, Akan.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Nancy Frishberg suggests that AdaSL may be related to the "gestural trade jargon used in the markets throughout West Africa".
[src:alipur-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Adamorobe Sign Language possesses distinct grammatical structures and vocabulary that set it apart from Ghanaian Sign Language and other national or international sign languages.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Unlike many urban sign languages that develop within educational institutions, AdaSL evolved organically within a close-knit community, resulting in unique syntactic constructions and simultaneous sign formations.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Its use is characterized by spatial grammar, classifier constructions, and gestures deeply embedded in the local culture.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] The language is not mutually intelligible with GSL, and many signs are specific to Adamorobe's cultural context, making it a rich subject of linguistic study.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] AdaSL also exhibits a lower reliance on fingerspelling compared to GSL, and it preserves several features that are considered archaic or absent in more standardized sign languages.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Deaf culture in Adamorobe is notably inclusive.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Deaf residents have historically participated fully in social, economic, and cultural activities.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Unlike many other societies, deafness in Adamorobe does not carry a stigma.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Instead, sign language has been a natural and respected form of communication, used not only by deaf individuals but also by hearing family members, friends, and neighbors.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] This integration is evident in communal gatherings, marketplaces, and traditional ceremonies where sign language is used openly.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] The social fabric of Adamorobe has long celebrated this coexistence, which has contributed to the resilience of its deaf community despite external pressures.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] AdaSL is believed to have emerged over 200 years ago, alongside the settlement's founding.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Genetic studies suggest that the high incidence of deafness in Adamorobe is due to a hereditary mutation passed down through generations.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] The earliest academic references to Adamorobe and its sign language date back to the mid-20th century, with researchers noting the community's unique integration of deaf individuals.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] In the 1960s and 1980s, the introduction of formal deaf education in Ghana led to the exposure of Adamorobe's deaf children to Ghanaian Sign Language, which is derived from American Sign Language (ASL).
[src:alipur-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] This exposure began to shift the linguistic practices of younger generations, who now tend to use GSL more frequently than AdaSL.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] A critical turning point in the village's history came in 1975 when the local chief instituted a ban on marriages between deaf individuals in an effort to reduce the incidence of hereditary deafness.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] While this policy effectively decreased the number of deaf births, it also inadvertently threatened the long-term survival of AdaSL.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Today, Adamorobe Sign Language faces significant challenges.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] The number of deaf individuals in the village has declined due to the marriage policy that discouraged unions between deaf people.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Additionally, the younger generation of deaf children is increasingly adopting Ghanaian Sign Language through formal education, which reduces the intergenerational transmission of AdaSL.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] The influence of urbanization and national language policies further accelerates the shift away from village sign languages.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Without deliberate preservation efforts, AdaSL risks becoming endangered or possibly extinct within the next few decades.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Several linguists and anthropologists have documented Adamorobe Sign Language extensively in recent years.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Their efforts aim to preserve the language's unique features and raise awareness of its cultural importance.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] However, there are limited formal initiatives within the village to revitalize or maintain AdaSL among younger generations.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Potential preservation strategies include community-based language programs, the development of AdaSL teaching materials, and the integration of the language into local schools.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Encouraging the use of AdaSL in social and cultural events could also contribute to its sustainability.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] The **Sultanate of Bijapur** was an early modern kingdom in the western Deccan and South India, ruled by the Muslim **Adil Shahi** (or **Adilshahi**) dynasty.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] Bijapur had been a *taraf* (province) of the Bahmani Kingdom prior to its independence in 1490 and before the kingdom's political decline in the last quarter of the 15th century.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] It was one of the Deccan sultanates, the collective name of the kingdom's five successor states.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] The Sultanate of Bijapur was one of the most powerful states on the Indian Subcontinent at its peak, second to the Mughal Empire which conquered it in 1686 under Aurangzeb.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] After emigrating to the Bahmani Sultanate, Yusuf Adil Shah rose through the ranks to be appointed governor of the province of Bijapur.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] In 1490, he created a *de facto* independent Bijapur state which became formally independent with the Bahmani collapse in 1518.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] The Bijapur Sultanate's borders changed considerably throughout its history.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] Its northern boundary remained relatively stable, straddling contemporary southern Maharashtra and northern Karnataka.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] The sultanate expanded southward, its first major conquest the Raichur Doab after defeating the Vijayanagara Empire at the Battle of Talikota in 1565.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] Later campaigns in the Karnatak and Carnatic extended Bijapur's borders and nominal authority as far south as Tanjore.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] For most of its history, Bijapur was bounded on the west by the Portuguese state of Goa, on the east by the Sultanate of Golconda, on the north by the Ahmednagar Sultanate and on the south by the Vijayanagara Empire and its succeeding Nayaka dynasties.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] The sultanate clashed incessantly with its neighbours.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] After the allied victory against Vijayanagara at Talikota in 1565, the state expanded through its conquest of the neighbouring Bidar Sultanate in 1619.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] The sultanate was then relatively stable, although it was damaged by the revolt of Shivaji (who founded an independent Maratha kingdom which become the Maratha Confederacy).
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] From the late 16th century, the greatest threat to Bijapur's security was the expansion of the Mughal Empire into the Deccan.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] Agreements and treaties imposed Mughal suzerainty on the Adil Shahs, by stages, until Bijapur's formal recognition of Mughal authority in 1636.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] The influence of their Mughal overlords and continual strife with the Marathas sapped the state of prosperity until the Mughal conquest of Bijapur in 1686.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] The former Bahmani provincial capital of Bijapur remained the sultanate's capital throughout its existence.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] After modest earlier developments, Ibrahim Adil Shah I and Ali Adil Shah I remodelled Bijapur with a citadel, city walls, and a congregational mosque.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] Their successors, Ibrahim Adil Shah II, Mohammed Adil Shah and Ali Adil Shah II, added palaces, mosques, a mausoleum and other structures (considered some of the finest examples of Deccani and Indo-Islamic architecture) to the capital.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] The founder of the dynasty, Yusuf Adil Shah, may have been a Georgian slave who was purchased by Mahmud Gawan.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] Other historians have said that he is of Persian or Turkmen origin.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] According to the contemporary historian Firishta, Yusuf was a son of the Ottoman Sultan Murad II; however, this is disputed by modern historians.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] Another theory is that he was an Aq Qoyunlu Turkman.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] Yusuf impressed Bahmani Sultan Muhammad Shah III, and he was appointed governor of Bijapur.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] Yusuf took advantage of Bahmani decline to establish himself as an independent sultan at Bijapur in 1490, pursuing the same goal Malik Ahmad Nizam Shah I had that year.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] He proclaimed Shia Islam as the official religion of his territorial holdings in 1503, following the lead of Shah Ismail of the Safavid dynasty.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] Yusuf conquered and annexed the Bahmani *taraf* of Gulbarga the following year and reinstated his Shia mandate shortly afterwards, a year after he revoked it under threat of invasion.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] A Portuguese Empire colonial expedition led by Afonso de Albuquerque exerted pressure on the major Adil Shahi port of Goa, conquering it in 1510; Yusuf retook the settlement two months later, but the Portuguese again conquered it in November of that year.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] Yusuf died in 1510, between these two clashes with the Portuguese, when his son Ismail Adil Shah was a boy.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] Ismail's regent, Kamal Khan, staged an unsuccessful coup against him; he was killed, and Ismail became the absolute ruler of Bijapur.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] In 1514, a dispute over Gulbaraga province led the rulers of the Ahmednagar, Golconda, and Bidar Sultanates to unsuccessfully invade Ismail Adil Shah's provinces.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] Krishnadevaraya, ruler of Vijayanagara, laid siege to the Bijapuri fort of Raichur in 1520.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] The siege continued for three months until the emperor's encounter with Ismail, who attempted to end it.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] Ismail was defeated by Krishnadevaraya in the Battle of Raichur; initially successful, with an advantage in artillery (in its first major appearance in a South Asian battle), Ismail was routed by the Vijayanagara forces in a surprise counter-attack which scattered much of his forces.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] Soon after Ismail's retreat, Krishnadevaraya captured the Raichur fort.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] In a later diplomatic conflict, Krishnadevaraya occupied Bijapur for an extended period and the sultan refused to see him.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] Ismail invaded the territory of Amir Barid I of Bidar in 1529, besieging his capital; Aladdin Imad Shah of Berar unsuccessfully tried to mediate the conflict.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] Amir Barid surrendered the fort of Bidar, which was looted by Ismail and his troops.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] Ismail recaptured Raichur and Mudgal from Vijayanagara the following year, after the death of Krishnadevaraya.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] Amir Barid agreed with Ismail to cede him the forts of Kalyani and Qandhar in exchange for Ismail's surrender of Bidar.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] Ismail was succeeded in 1534 by Mallu Adil Shah, whose reign was short-lived.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] Installed by a prominent Bijapuri noble, Asad Khan, he is noted for incompetence; Vijayanagara invaded the sultanate and seize the Raichur Doab from the Adil Shahis.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] Mallu Adil Shah was soon blinded and removed from power.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] Ibrahim Adil Shah I, Ismail's son, succeeded Mallu the following year.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] He established Sunni Islam as the state religion and made anti-Westerner changes, abolishing the use of Persian in some administrative tasks (although it remained the sultanate's official language) and replacing many Westerners with Deccanis.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] Ibrahim also invaded the Vijayanagara Empire; he pillaged a number of cities and besieged the capital, Vijayanagara, but did not seize any territory in the long term and returned home with only non-territorial rewards.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] In another conflict with the Portuguese, Ibrahim ceded two ports in the fear that trade through Goa might be cut off from the Adil Shahis.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] His kingdom was invaded four times by Ahmednagar Sultanate forces, the sultanate's greatest adversary.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] The war was a defeat for the Bijapuri–Bidar side, who ceded a northern district of the Bijapur Sultanate to Ahmednagar.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] Burhan and Ibrahim allowed Ahmednagar freedom to expand in Bidar if Bijapur had the same freedom to annex lands from Vijayanagara; Ibrahim imprisoned Ali Barid Shahi of Bidar despite their former alliance, although he was later freed by Jamsheed (who wanted a buffer state in the Deccan).
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] Burhan Nizam Shah besieged the Bijapuri city of Solapur four times, but did not retain it until a third invasion which occupied territory on the southern border.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] Burhan advanced in a fourth invasion in 1553 with Vijayanagara almost to the Bijapuri capital, but retreated due to failing health.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] Ali Adil Shah I, who ascended the throne in 1558, reestablished Shia Islam as the state religion.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] He unsuccessfully asked Hussain Nizam Shah I for the return of Solapur and Kaliyani (both seized in Ahmednagari invasions) and then invaded the Nizam Shahi kingdom with assistance from Vijayanagara's *de facto* ruler Rama Raya and Ibrahim Qutb Shah, besieging Ahmednagar and other cities.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] Hussain sued for peace in 1561, submitting to Rama Raya and returning Kaliyani to Ali Adil Shah.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] In 1563, Hussain attempted to regain Kaliyani and again besieged it.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] Ahmednagar was besieged by Ali, and Hussain was forced to abandon his siege of Kaliyani; the only beneficiary of the conflict was Vijayanagara, who gained territory from invading Golconda.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] Vijayanagara negotiated additional land from Bijapur, including the cities of Yadgir and Bagalkote.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] Wary of Vijayanagara's growing power, Ali allied his forces with the sultans of Golconda, Ahmednagar and Bidar (despite past conflicts) and defeated the Vijayanagara Empire in the 1565 Battle of Talikota.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] Rama Raya was beheaded after his capture by Deccani forces.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] Vijayanagara and nearby cities were sacked and looted (Vijayanagara for five to six months), and historian Hermann Goetz said that this prompted the emigration of much of Vijayanagara's population to Bijapur.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] The Raichur Doab and its surrounding area were returned to Bijapur.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] The Vijayanagara military was demolished, and the kingdom was a shell of its former self.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] Ali I then fortified Bijapur with a wall, which facilitated the further centralization of authority.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] Subsequent architectural projects encouraged the growth of the city and its skilled class.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] Another conflict between Ahmednagar and Bijapur arose in 1567; although Ali invaded Ahmednagar and his forces occupied a number of forts, the war ended in a stalemate.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] A 1570 conflict with the Portuguese began with the hope of expelling them from India, but Ali was defeated after a number of encounters the following year.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] He then annexed more land from Vijayanagara in a campaign which lasted until 1575, conquering Adoni and much of the Carnatic.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] Ali also began a campaign to capture the Karnatak; according to Richard M.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] Eaton, his "armies destroyed two to three hundred Hindu temples" which were replaced with Shia buildings.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] By 1576, land gained under Ali I had doubled the sultanate's holdings.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] He forged diplomatic relations with the Mughals, Ottomans, and Safavids during his reign, which Eaton says brought the sultanate into the *dar al-islam*.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] Ali I had no son, and his nine-year-old nephew Ibrahim II was set on the throne in 1580.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] Control of the regency was contested by Kamal Khan and, later, by the Habshi Dilawar Khan (who reverted the state religion to Sunni Islam).
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] Dilawar was deposed by Ibrahim II in 1590.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] Ibrahim's rule was characterised by prosperity and patronage; Sufism thrived, with its adherents and others flocking to Bijapur because of his talent as a musician and poet.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] Ibrahim suppressed a 1594 rebellion by his brother, Ismail, who was aided by Burhan II of Ahmednagar.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] Despite their past quarrels, the Adil Shahis formed an alliance in 1597 with Ahmednagar and Golconda to deter further Mughal advances in the Deccan.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] The alliance, led by a Bijapuri general, was defeated despite a three-to-one numerical advantage.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] Ahmednagar fell to the Mughals in 1600, but Ibrahim continued to support the eventually-successful resistance of Malik Ambar.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] Ibrahim II founded the city of Nauraspur in 1599, three kilometers west of Bijapur, as a planned center of learning and art; never completed, it was destroyed in 1624 by Malik Ambar's forces.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] In 1618, the sultan lost the fortress of Janjira to the independent Habshi state of western India.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] The following year, Bijapur conquered the neighbouring Bidar Sultanate (although control of the state was achieved as early as 1580).
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] Bidar was in neither sphere of influence and Malik Ambar, *de facto* ruler of Ahmednagar, invaded Bijapur; after reaching the capital relatively unopposed, he withdrew.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] In addition to his work on Nauraspur, the sultan built the Ibrahim Rauza.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] Muhammad Adil Shah succeeded his father, Ibrahim II, in 1627.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] Under Muhammad, the Sultanate of Bijapur reached its zenith.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] The first Mughal invasion of the sultanate was in 1631 by Shah Jahan, who reached (and besieged) Bijapur but was ultimately unsuccessful.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] In 1636, Bijapur signed a treaty agreeing to pay tribute to the Mughal emperor and acknowledge Mughal authority.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] As a reward for this gesture, the recent Mughal conquest of Ahmednagar was partitioned between the two states.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] The treaty began a period of relative peace with the Mughals, allowing for more southern conquests; Bijapur reached its territorial peak, with its borders stretching from the Arabian Sea to the Bay of Bengal.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] Muhammad Adil Shah died in 1656 after a decade-long, paralyzing illness.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] Ali Adil Shah II inherited a troubled kingdom which was invaded by Mughal forces in 1657 under viceroy Aurangzeb, who captured Bidar and other forts and reached Bijapur before retreating; Aurangzeb annexed much of the occupied territory, including Bidar.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] The stability of the Bijapur Sultanate was again affected by trouble with the Marathas, who persisted with raids and rebellions.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] Bijapuri general Afzal Khan was sent to subdue Shivaji in 1659, but he was murdered and his home fort of Pratapgarh was captured in a confrontation with Shivaji.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] Despite further Maratha advances in the north, Ali continued his southern campaigns in the Karnatak and Carnatic and captured Thanjavur and other cities from the Nayakas from 1659 to 1663.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] Sikandar Adil Shah, the last Adil Shahi sultan, ruled for fourteen troubled years.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] His reign saw a number of civil wars, internal strife and unrest, particularly over his regency; he was four years old at his accession.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] Khawas Khan, Sikandar's first regent and leader of the Deccani faction, took control of the state before his removal from power.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] Shivaji founded an independent Maratha kingdom which became the Maratha Confederacy in 1674, with *de facto* control of much of the Adil Shahis' original territory in the Deccan.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] He undid almost all the southern Bijapuri conquests over the following years, annexing the territory and renewing efforts to conquer the remaining Muslim Deccan states after Shivaji's death in 1680.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] In April 1685, Mughal forces led by Aurangzeb began a siege of Bijapur; at its conclusion, on 12 September 1686, the Sultanate of Bijapur came to an end.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] The capital and its surrounding territory were annexed into an eponymous *subah*, and Sikandar was sent into Mughal captivity.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] The sultanate's architecture, a subset of Deccani architecture, was a variant of Indo-Islamic architecture influenced by that of the Middle East.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] Adil Shahi architecture was of good quality with a localized, unique nature.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] It was characterised by large domes and dargahs (Sufi shrines), complex turrets, geometric and Arabic (or Persian) calligraphic designs, and decorated friezes of tholobates.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] Yusuf Adil Shah, the first sultan, began by expanding two dargahs at Gulbarga with minarets.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] The first building characteristic of Adil Shahi architecture was a Jama Masjid built during the reign of Ibrahim Adil Shah I.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] The primary Jami Masjid of Bijapur, built under Ali I, was commissioned in 1576.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] The largest of any structure of its type in the Deccan when it was built, Eaton calls it "one of the most imposing and magnificent" in the region.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] Under Ibrahim II, the sultanate's most prolific patron, Adil Shahi architecture focused on intricate carvings and detail and adopted Hindu–Muslim syncretism; this change is seen in the Malika Jahan Begum mosque built by the sultan in 1586.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] His most notable commissioned work was the eponymous Ibrahim Rauza, completed in 1626, with a mosque built in honour of his wife and a mausoleum for his family.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] Mohammed Adil Shah facilitated the creation of the Gol Gumbaz, his mausoleum and one of Bijapur's greatest monuments.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] It is supported by large, arched recesses and a massive dome, the largest in the Islamic world when it was nearly completed at Muhammad's death in 1656.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] The last major Adil Shahi architectural project was the Bara Kaman, Ali Adil Shah II's unfinished mausoleum, which halted construction with his death in 1672.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] The Adil Shahis used miniature painting from the Bijapur school of Deccan painting.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] Miniature painting was virtually nonexistent in the sultanate before the reign of Ali I, but became widespread under his rule and flourished under Ibrahim II and his successors.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] The Bijapur school of painting was rooted in Persian miniature painting and culture, and was usually baroque in style.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] In contrast to North Indian contemporary painting, it seldom depicted events and scenes of war but focused on atmospheric, picturesque fantasies and dreams, avoiding logic in general.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] The Adil Shahi sultans promoted the development of writing in the Deccani language, and Bijapur was a center of its early literary evolution.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] Ibrahim II, a skilled writer of Deccani Urdu literature, was one of its earliest proponents.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] He wrote the *Kitab-i Nauras*, a Deccani musical poetry work, and patronized a number of poets and their work.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] His poet laureate, the Persian Muhammad Zuhuri, wrote the *Saqinama*, a collection of lyric poetry.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] After entering Ibrahim's service in 1604 and gaining his trust, Firishta followed the sultan's suggestion and wrote the *Tarikh-i Firishta*, his history of the medieval Deccan which is the basis for much modern historiography on the region and period.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] Nusrati, a noted Deccani poet, wrote the later romantic poem *Gulshan-i 'Ishq* and a narrative of the sultan's conquests under the patronage of Ali Adil Shah II.
[src:alipur-sign-language/adil-shahi-dynasty] Nine sultans ruled the Sultanate of Bijapur from 1490 to 1686, with the title of Sultan of Bijapur.
[src:alipur-sign-language/afghan-sign-language] Education for the deaf in Afghanistan grew out of educational efforts among Afghan refugees in Peshawar in the 1990s, making Pakistani Sign Language (IPSL) an early influence on Afghan Sign Language.
[src:alipur-sign-language/afghan-sign-language] The first formal school for the deaf in Afghanistan was established in Jalalabad in 1995 by SERVE Afghanistan.
[src:alipur-sign-language/afghan-sign-language] That same year, SERVE began a project to document Afghan Sign Language, and later produced a trilingual (Dari, Pashto, and English) dictionary of Afghan Sign Language.
[src:alipur-sign-language/afghan-sign-language] The language derives from the Deaf-community sign language of Jalalabad, and it is not known what connection it may have, if any, with the sign languages of other cities with established deaf populations, which are principally Mazar-i-Sharif, Herat, and Kandahar.
[src:alipur-sign-language/afghan-sign-language] Early analysis suggested some AFSL signs may have come from Pakistani Sign Language (IPSL) or American Sign Language (ASL), although intensive research on this link was not undertaken at the time.
[src:alipur-sign-language/afghan-sign-language] While IPSL's influence would have been due to regional exchange, ASL could have had an influence due to its use by some SERVE teachers in its early programming.
[src:alipur-sign-language/afghan-sign-language] Fingerspelling was introduced to AFSL in the late 1990s, after SERVE educators visited the Holy Land Institute for the Deaf in Jordan.
[src:alipur-sign-language/afghan-sign-language] Thus, Jordanian Sign Language and AFSL share a fingerspelling alphabet, although AFSL also introduced some additional letters to represent letters not found in the Arabic script.
[src:alipur-sign-language/afghan-sign-language] Afghan Sign Language is primarily spoken in Jalalabad and Kabul, which have three large schools for the deaf between them.
[src:alipur-sign-language/afghan-sign-language] Smaller deaf populations who use AFSL are also found in major urban centers in the country, those being Mazar-e Sharif, Herat, and Kandahar.
[src:alipur-sign-language/afghan-sign-language] The majority of profoundly deaf Afghans (estimated at 30,000 in 2013) have never attended a school for the deaf.
[src:alipur-sign-language/akitiri-sign-language] Akitiri is often used when speech is impractical or not preferred and this includes when people are communicating across long distances, hunting, when wishing to speak privately and during ceremony and times of mourning.
[src:alipur-sign-language/akitiri-sign-language] Hand signs are also frequently used alongside speech and is more commonly used by women of the community.
[src:alipur-sign-language/akitiri-sign-language] In many Kaytetye communities fluency in Akitiri is highly valued but, due to the impacts of colonisation, use is declining and younger generations often use it in a different or simplified way.
[src:alipur-sign-language/akitiri-sign-language] A 2023 project to revitalise the Kaytetye language and Akitiri sign language was the Kaytetyemoji app which created 122 emojis including 44 specific to life on Kaytetye country.
[src:alipur-sign-language/akitiri-sign-language] These emoji's often directly reflect the hand signs of Akitiri and, as part of the development of the app, many younger generations were taught new signs to them.
[src:alipur-sign-language/alipur-sign-language] During his study, Panda found out that the proportion of deaf population in Alipur was of approximately 0.75%, against 0.41% on national average (data from the 2011 census).
[src:alipur-sign-language/alipur-sign-language] The deaf community of Alipur helped Panda in his researches, particularly Mr.
[src:alipur-sign-language/alipur-sign-language] Fazil Raza, a 53 year old former gram panchayat chief, who helped set up the Alipur Unity Society for the Deaf.
[src:alipur-sign-language/alipur-sign-language] Fazil Raza helped with translation from English to the sign language, conducted survey with the help of other members of the community, and served as an informator for the documentation of the language.
[src:alipur-sign-language/alipur-sign-language] Endogamous marriages in the town have led to this large population of deaf, but a deaf man cannot marry a deaf woman.
[src:alipur-sign-language/alipur-sign-language] Since there are no public records in the town, it is difficult to establish the veracity of this information.
[src:alipur-sign-language/alipur-sign-language] The sign language is used by many hearing people as well, with level of fluency that greatly varies.
[src:alipur-sign-language/alipur-sign-language] The language has a variety of ways to express numbers, using additions and subtractions to express numbers with high complexity.
[src:alipur-sign-language/alipur-sign-language] Mouth movements can be added to express bigger numbers.
[src:alipur-sign-language/alipur-sign-language] The majority of inhabitants in the town are Shia Muslim.
[src:alipur-sign-language/alipur-sign-language] The Shia Muslim population descend from Bijapur after the down fall of Adil Shahi Dynasty and are proud of their culture and history.
[src:alipur-sign-language/alipur-sign-language] The younger generation is less interested in using the village sign language.
[src:alipur-sign-language/alipur-sign-language] Mobility and technology give them access to the Internet and they travel to Bengaluru where they learn Indian Sign Language and American Sign Language.
[src:alipur-sign-language/alipur-sign-language] The lack of formal education is nevertheless a barrier for them to be able to use script-based applications (like text messaging) and there are not many employment opportunities.
[src:alipur-sign-language/alipur-sign-language] A better understanding of the situation of the language could be beneficial for the population.
[src:alipur-sign-language/alipur-sign-language] Nobel School (A Private School in a Village) has recently started classes for the deaf children.
[src:alipur-sign-language/alipur-sign-language] However, there is a hope to re-open the government school for special children.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] American Sign Language (ASL) has grammar just like any other sign language or spoken language.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The study of ASL structure dates back to William Stokoe, Dorothy Casterline, and Carl Croneberg in the 1960s.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Since then, linguists have been describing patterns in ASL responsible for creating meaning at all kinds of levels, from the word, to phrases and sentences and beyond.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Not all of these linguists ascribe to the same theoretical framework, using various theories, models, and analyses.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Some analyze the language from a generative linguistics perspective, while others from a cognitive linguistics perspective.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In ASL morphology, publications have historically categorized morphological processes under two umbrellas: derivational morphology and inflectional morphology.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Derivational morphology is the process by which new units can be created in a language, and like any other language, this process has been observed in a variety of forms in ASL.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] One form of derivational morphology occurs when a change in movement changes the sign's meaning – often between a noun and a verb.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This may be done either by reduplicating the movement of the verb if the verb has a single movement, or by restraining (making smaller and faster) the movement of the verb if it already has repeated movement.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, the noun CHAIR is derived from the verb SIT through reduplication.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Another way of deriving new words in ASL is via the process of compounding, which often differ in meaning from their constituent signs.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, the signs FACE and STRONG compound to create a new sign FACE^STRONG, meaning 'to resemble'.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Some linguists have analyzed various compounds as a type of suffixation.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Agent nouns may be derived from verbs by adding the sign, or suffix, AGENT and deleting the final hold of the verb, e.g.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Superlatives have also been analyzed as created by a formed by suffixation, e.g.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, Ted Supalla's work on ASL verbs of motion analyzed these signs as consisting of many different affixes, articulated simultaneously according to complex grammatical constraints.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This differs from the concatenative morphology of many spoken languages, which except for suprasegmental features, such as tone, are tightly constrained by the sequential nature of voice sounds.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Numeral incorporation is another derivational morphological process that has been studied in ASL.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Certain types of signs, for example, those relating to time and age, may incorporate numbers by assimilating their handshape.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, the word for 'week' has handshape /B/ with the weak hand and /1/ with the active hand; the active hand's handshape may be changed to the handshape of any number up to 9 to indicate that many weeks.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Some linguists have analyzed this phenomenon as a type of affixation.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Signs of age, for example, will begin with a touch at the chin.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] They argue that this touch functions as a prefix which completely assimilates with the handshape of the corresponding age number.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For instance, the word for 'nine' is signed with an /F/ handshape produced ipsilaterally in front of the signer's shoulder.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The chin-touch in 'nine years old' can be analyzed as an affix, which is then produced with this same /F/ handshape.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For 'three years old', however, the prefix is made with a 3 handshape.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Inflectional morphology adds units of language to other words.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, this would be changing 'watch' to 'watches' or 'watching.' In ASL, the sign may remain unchanged as WATCH, or the meaning may change based on non-manual markers (NMM).
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] ASL morphology demonstrates reduplication and indexicality as well.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] There are about 20 non-manual modifiers in ASL, which are either adjectival or adverbial.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Rather than relying on sequential affixes, ASL makes heavy use of simultaneous modification of signs.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] One example of this is found in the aspectual system (see below); another is *numeral incorporation:* There are several families of two-handed signs which require one of the hands to take the handshape of a numeral.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, drawing the dominant hand lengthwise across the palm and fingers of a flat B hand indicates a number of weeks; the dominant hand takes the form of a numeral from one to nine to specify how many weeks.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] There are analogous signs for 'weeks ago' and 'weeks from now', etc., though in practice several of these signs are only found with the lower numerals.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] ASL also has a system of classifiers which may be incorporated into signs.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] These classifiers are moved through sign space to iconically represent the actions of their referents.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, an ILY hand may 'lift off' or 'land on' a horizontal B hand to sign an aircraft taking off or landing; a 3 hand may be brought down on a B hand to sign parking a car; and a G hand may be brought toward a V hand to represent one person approaching two.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The frequency of classifier use depends greatly on genre, occurring at a rate of 17.7% in narratives but only 1.1% in casual speech and 0.9% in formal speech.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Frames are a morphological device that may be unique to sign languages (Liddell 2004).
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] They are incomplete sets of the features which make up signs, and they combine with existing signs, absorbing features from them to form a derived sign.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] It is the frame which specifies the number and nature of segments in the resulting sign, while the basic signs it combines with lose all but one or two of their original features.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] One, the WEEKLY frame, consists of a simple downward movement.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] It combines with the signs for the days of the week, which then lose their inherent movement.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, 'Monday' consists of an M/O hand made with a circling movement.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] 'MondayWEEKLY' (that is, 'on Mondays') is therefore signed as an M/O hand that drops downward, but without the circling movement.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] A similar ALL DAY frame (a sideward pan) combines with times of the day, such as 'morning' and 'afternoon', which likewise keep their handshape and location but lose their original movement.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Numeral incorporation (see above) also uses frames.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] However, in ASL frames are most productively utilized for verbal aspect.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] While there is no grammatical tense in ASL, there are numerous verbal aspects.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] These are produced by modulating the verb: through reduplication, by placing the verb in an aspectual frame (see above), or with a combination of these means.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] An example of an aspectual frame is the *unrealized inceptive* aspect ('just about to X'), illustrated here with the verb 'to tell'.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] 'To tell' is an indexical (directional) verb, where the index finger (a G hand) begins with a touch to the chin and then moves outward to point out the recipient of the telling.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The handshape throughout the sign is whichever is required by the final hold, in this case a G hand.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The variety of aspects in ASL can be illustrated by the verb 'to be sick', which involves the middle finger of the Y/8 hand touching the forehead, and which can be modified by a large number of frames.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Several of these involve reduplication, which may but need not be analyzed as part of the frame.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] These modulations readily combine with each other to create yet finer distinctions.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Not all verbs take all aspects, and the forms they do take will not necessarily be completely analogous to the verb illustrated here.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Conversely, not all aspects are possible with this one verb.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Aspect is unusual in ASL in that transitive verbs derived for aspect lose their transitivity.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Reduplication is also used for expressing verbal number.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Verbal number indicates that the action of the verb is repeated; in the case of ASL it is apparently limited to transitive verbs, where the motion of the verb is either extended or repeated to cover multiple object or recipient loci.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] (Simple plurality of action can also be conveyed with reduplication, but without indexing any object loci; in fact, such aspectual forms do not allow objects, as noted above.) There are specific dual forms (and for some signers trial forms), as well as plurals.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] If the singular verb uses reduplication, that is lost in the dual and plural forms.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] There are three types of personal name signs in ASL: fingerspelled, arbitrary, and descriptive.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Fingerspelled names are simply spelled out letter-by-letter.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Arbitrary name signs only refer to a person's name, while descriptive name signs refer to a person's personality or physical characteristics.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Once given, names are for life, apart from changing from one of the latter types to an arbitrary sign in childhood.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Name signs are usually assigned by another member of the Deaf community, and signal inclusion in that community.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Name signs are not used to address people, as names are in English, but are used only for third-person reference, and usually only when the person is absent.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The majority of people, probably well in excess of 90%, have arbitrary name signs.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] These are initialized signs: The handshape is the initial of one of the English names of the person, usually the first.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The sign may occur in neutral space, with a tremble; with a double-tap (as a noun) at one of a limited number of specific locations, such as the side of the chin, the temple, or the elbow; or moving across a location or between two locations, with a single tap at each.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Single-location signs are simpler in connotation, like English "Vee"; double-location signs are fancier, like English "Veronica".
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Sam Supalla (1992) collected 525 simple arbitrary name signs like these.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] There are two constraints on arbitrary signs.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] That is, it should not duplicate an existing ASL word.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Second, there should not be more than one person with the name sign in the local community.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] If a person moves to a new community where someone already has their name sign, then the newcomer is obligated to modify theirs.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This is usually accomplished by compounding the handshape, so that the first tap of the sign takes the initial of the person's first English name, and the second tap takes the initial of their last name.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] There are potentially thousands of such compound-initial signs.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Descriptive name signs are not initialized, but rather use non-core ASL signs.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] They tend to be assigned and used by children, rather like "Blinky" in English.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Parents do not give such names to their children, but most Deaf people do not have deaf parents and are assigned their name sign by classmates in their first school for the deaf.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] At most 10% of Deaf people retain such name signs into adulthood..
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Arbitrary name signs became established very early in the history of ASL.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Descriptive name signs refer to a person's appearance or personality.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The two systems, arbitrary and descriptive, are sometimes combined, usually for humorous purposes.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Hearing people learning ASL are also often assigned combined name signs.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This is not traditional for Deaf people.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Sometimes people with very short English names, such as "Ann" or "Lee", or ones that flow easily, such as "Larry", may never acquire a name sign, but may instead be referred to with finger-spelling.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Non-Manual Markers (NMM), or Non-Manual Signals (NMS) are communication methods not found in the hands.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] They typically consist of facial expressions and body language.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] NMMs can change the grammar of a sentence.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Not every sign uses non-manual markers, but for many others, these markers determine what sign is being produced.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Some examples of non-manual markers would be the shifting of shoulders, the lowering or raising of eyebrows, a head nod or shake, scrunching of the nose, pursing of the lips, or an open mouth.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] NMMs are important for indicating if a question is being asked.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For *WH-* questions, the eyebrows are lowered, and for *YES/NO* questions, the eyebrows are raised.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] It is hard to indicate if a question is being asked otherwise without facial indicators.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Another example would be between *I UNDERSTAND* and *I DON'T UNDERSTAND*.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The sign for this is the same; the hand is held up near the forehead with the palm facing the self.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] If the person is nodding and has their eyebrows raised, it means *I UNDERSTAND*.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] If they are shaking their head with eyebrows lowered, it means *I DON'T UNDERSTAND*.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Understanding ASL grammar requires understanding the difference between a signer's dominant and non-dominant hand.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] If a person is right-handed, then their right hand is their dominant hand, and their left hand is their non-dominant hand.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Almost all signs are completed with the more active, dominant hand, while the non-dominant hand serves as a base.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For signs requiring two hands, the dominant hand performs more of the active component.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] ASL is a subject–verb–object (SVO) language.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] However, OSV is also an accepted sentence form.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The default SVO word order is sometimes altered by processes including topicalization and null elements.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This is marked either with non-manual signals like eyebrow or body position, or with prosodic marking such as pausing.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] These non-manual grammatical markings (such as eyebrow movement or head-shaking) may optionally spread over the c-command domain of the node which it is attached to.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] However, ASL is a pro-drop language, and when the manual sign that a non-manual grammatical marking is attached to is omitted, the non-manual marking obligatorily spreads over the c-command domain.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The full sentence structure in ASL is [topic] [subject] verb [object] [subject–pronoun–tag].
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Topics and *tags* are both indicated with non-manual features, and both give a great deal of flexibility to ASL word order.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Within a noun phrase, the word order is noun–number and noun–adjective.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] ASL does not have a copula (linking 'to be' verb).
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In addition to its basic topic–comment structure, ASL typically places an adjective after a noun, though it may occur before the noun for stylistic purposes.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Numerals also occur after the noun, a very rare pattern among oral languages.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Adverbs, however, occur before the verbs.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Most of the time adverbs are simply the same sign as an adjective, distinguished by the context of the sentence.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] When the scope of the adverb is the entire clause, as in the case of time, it comes before the topic.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] ASL makes heavy use of time-sequenced ordering, meaning that events are signed in the order in which they occur.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, for *I was late to class last night because my boss handed me a huge stack of work after lunch yesterday,* one would sign 'YESTERDAY LUNCH FINISH, BOSS GIVE-me WORK BIG-STACK, NIGHT CLASS LATE-me'.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In stories, however, ordering is malleable, since one can choose to sequence the events either in the order in which they occurred or in the order in which one found out about them.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] It has been claimed that tense in ASL is marked adverbially, and that ASL lacks a separate category of tense markers.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] (1992, 1995) argue that "Tense" (T) is indeed a distinct category of syntactic head, and that the T node can be occupied either by a modal (e.g.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Aspect may be marked either by verbal inflection or by separate lexical items.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] As noted above, in ASL aspectually marked verbs cannot take objects.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] To deal with this, the object must be known from context so that it does not need to be further specified.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] It may be used as the topic of the utterance at hand.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Of these two strategies, the first is the more common.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] A topic sets off background information that will be discussed in the following main clause.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Topicalization is used productively in ASL and often results in surface forms that do not follow the basic SVO word order.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In order to non-manually mark topics, the eyebrows are raised and the head is tilted back during the production of a topic.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The head is often lowered toward the end of the sign, and sometimes the sign is followed rapidly nodding the head.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Another way topics may be signed is by shifting the body.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The signer may use the space on one side of his/her body to sign the topic, and then shifts to the other side for the rest of the sentence.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] ASL utterances do not require topics, but their use is extremely common.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] They are used for purposes of information flow, to set up referent loci (see above), and to supply objects for verbs which are grammatically prevented from taking objects themselves (see below).
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] However, people tend to want to set up the object of their concern first and then discuss what happened to it.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] There are three types of non-manual topic markers, all of which involve raised eyebrows.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The three types of non-manual topic markers are used with different types of topics and in different contexts, and the topic markings cannot spread over other elements in the utterance.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Topics can be moved from and remain null in the main clause of an utterance, or topics can be base-generated and either be co-referential to either the subject or object in the main clause or be related to the subject of object by a semantic property.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The first type of non-manual marking, topic marking 1 (tm1), is only used with a moved topic.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Tm1 is characterized by raised eyebrows, widened eyes, and head tilted backwards.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] At the end of the sign the head moves down and there is a pause, often with an eye blink, before the sentence is continued.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Topic marking 2 (tm2) and topic marking 3 (tm3) are both used with base-generated topics.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Tm2 is characterized by raised eyebrows, widened eyes, and the head tilted backwards and to the side.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Toward the end of the sign the head moves forward and to the opposite side, and there is a pause and often an eye blink before continuing.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For tm3 the eyebrows are raised and the eyes are opened wide, the head starts tilted down and jerks up and down, the lips are opened and raised, and the head is nodded rapidly a few times before pausing and continuing the sentence.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Although both tm2 and tm3 accompany base-generated topics, they are used in different contexts.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Tm2 is used to introduce new information and change the topic of a conversation to something that the signer is going to subsequently characterize, while tm3 is used to introduce new information that the signer believes is already known by his/her interlocutor.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Tm2 may be used with any base-generated topic, whereas only topics that are co-referential with an argument in the sentence may be marked with tm3.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] ASL sentences may have up to two marked topics.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Possible combinations of topic types are two tm2 topics, two tm3 topics, tm2 preceding tm1, tm3 preceding tm1, and tm2 preceding tm3.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Sentences with these topic combinations in the opposite orders or with two tm1 topics are considered ungrammatical by native signers.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Relative clauses are signaled by tilting back the head and raising the eyebrows and upper lip.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This is done during the performance of the entire clause.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] where the brackets here indicate the duration of the non-manual features.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] If the sign 'recently' were made without these features, it would lie outside the relative clause, and the meaning would change to "the dog which chased the cat recently came home".
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Negated clauses may be signaled by shaking the head during the entire clause.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] A topic, however, cannot be so negated; the headshake can only be produced during the production of the main clause.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In addition, in many communities, negation is put at the end of the clause, unless there is a wh- question word.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, the sentence, "I thought the movie was not good," could be signed as, "BEFORE MOVIE ME SEE, THINK WHAT?
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] There are two manual signs that negate a sentence, NOT and NONE, which are accompanied by a shake of the head.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] There are three types of questions with different constructions in ASL: wh- questions, yes/no questions, and rhetorical questions.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Non-manual grammatical markings are grammatical and semantic features that do not include the use of hands.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] They can include mouth shape, eye gazes, facial expressions, body shifting, head tilting, and eyebrow raising.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Non-manual grammatical markings can also aid in identifying sentence type, which is especially relevant to our discussion of different types of interrogatives.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Wh-questions can be formed in a variety of ways in ASL.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The wh-word can appear solely at the end of the sentence, solely at the beginning of the sentence, at both the beginning and end of the sentence (see section 4.4.2.1 on 'double-occurring wh-words', or in situ (i.e. where the wh-word is in the sentence structure before movement occurs)).
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Manual wh-signs are also accompanied by a non-manual grammatical marking (see section 4.4.1), which can include a variety of features.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This non-manual grammatical marking can spread optionally over the entire wh-phrase or just a small part.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Some languages have very few wh-words, where context and discourse are sufficient to elicit the information that one needs.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] ASL has many different wh-words, with certain wh-words having multiple variations.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] A list of the wh-words of ASL can be found below.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] As mentioned above, ASL possesses wh-questions with word initial placement, word final placement, in situ structure, but the most unique style of wh-word occurrence in ASL is where the wh-word occurs twice, copied in final position.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This doubling can be seen in the table below.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This doubling provides a useful template to analyze two separate analyses about whether wh-words move rightward or leftward in ASL.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] While some researchers argue for rightward movement in wh- questions such as Aarons and Neidle, others, including Petronio and Lillo-Martin, have argued that ASL has leftward movement and wh- words that appear to the right of the clause move by other processes.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Both analyses agree upon the fact that there is wh-movement present in these interrogative phrases, but it is a matter of what direction the wh-movement is moving in that causes controversy.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The leftward movement analysis is congruent with cross-linguistic data that wh-movement is always leftward.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] It can be seen as the less controversial of the two proposals.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The main arguments presented by the Leftward Wh-movement analysis are: That the spec-CP is on the left, that the wh-movement is leftward, and that the final wh-word in a sentence is a base-generated double.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This is illustrated in the syntax tree located to the right of this paragraph.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Arguments for leftward movement are based on the facts that if wh-movement in ASL were rightward, ASL would be an exception to cross-linguistic generalizations that wh-movement is leftward.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] It has also been hypothesized that wh-elements cannot be topicalized, as topicalized elements must be presupposed and interrogatives are not.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This would be detrimental to the rightward analysis, as they are analyzing the doubled wh-word as a 'base generated topic'.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The rightward movement analysis is a newer, more abstract argument of how wh-movement occurs in ASL.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The main arguments for rightward movement begin by analyzing spec-CP as being on the right, the wh-movement as being rightward, and as the initial wh-word as a base-generated topic.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This can be seen in the syntax tree on the right.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] One of the rightward movement analysis' main arguments is in regards to the non-manual grammatical markings, and their optional spreading over the sentence.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In ASL the use of non-manual grammatical markings is optional depending on the type of wh-question being asked.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In the rightward analysis both partial and full spreading of non-manual grammatical markers can be accounted for due to the association with the +WH feature over its c-command domain.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In the leftward analysis, the partial or full spreading of non manual grammatical markings cannot be accounted for in this same way.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The leftward movement analysis requires wh-marking to extend over the entirety of the question, regardless (which is not what is attested in ASL).
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In spoken language Yes/no questions will oftentimes differ in their word order from the statement form.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In ASL, yes/no questions are marked by the non-manual grammatical markings (as discussed in section 4.4.1).
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This eyebrow raise, slight tilt of the head and lean forward are what indicate that a yes/no question is being asked, without any change in word order from the statement form.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] There is speculation amongst linguists that these non-manual grammatical markings that indicate a yes/no questions are similar to the question intonation of spoken languages.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Yes/no questions differ from wh-questions as they do not differ in word order from the original statement form of the sentence, whereas wh-questions do.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] As well, in yes/no questions, the non-manual marking must be used over the whole utterance in order for it to be judged as a statement opposed to a question.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The yes/no question is the same word order as the statement form of the sentence, with the addition of non-manual grammatical markings.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Non-manual grammatical markings are also used for rhetorical questions, which are questions that do not intend to elicit an answer.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] To distinguish the non-manual marking for rhetorical questions from that of yes/no questions, the body is in a neutral position opposed to tilted forward, and the head is tilted in a different way than in yes/no questions.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Rhetorical questions are much more common in ASL than in English.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] [I LIKE]NEGATIVE [WHAT?]RHETORICAL, GARLIC.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This strategy is commonly used instead of signing the word 'because' for clarity or emphasis.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] PASTA I EAT ENJOY TRUE [WHY?]RHETORICAL, ITALIAN I.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In ASL signers set up regions of space (loci) for specific referents (see above); these can then be referred to indexically by pointing at those locations with pronouns and indexical verbs.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] That is, they point to their referent, or to a locus representing their referent.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] If the referent is not physically present, the speaker identifies the referent and then points to a location (the *locus)* in the sign space near their body.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This locus can then be pointed at to refer to the referent.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Theoretically, any number of loci may be set up, as long as the signer and recipient remember them all, but in practice, no more than eight loci are used.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Meier 1990 demonstrates that only two grammatical persons are distinguished in ASL: First person and non-first person, as in Damin.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Both persons come in several numbers as well as with signs such as 'my' and 'by myself'.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Meier provides several arguments for believing that ASL does not formally distinguish second from third person.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, when pointing to a person that is physically present, a pronoun is equivalent to either 'you' or '(s)he' depending on the discourse.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] There is nothing in the sign itself, nor in the direction of eye gaze or body posture, that can be relied on to make this distinction.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] That is, the same formal sign can refer to any of several second or third persons, which the indexic nature of the pronoun makes clear.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In English, indexic uses also occur, as in 'I need *you* to go to the store and *you* to stay here', but not so ubiquitously.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In contrast, several first-person ASL pronouns, such as the plural possessive ('our'), look different from their non-first-person equivalents, and a couple of pronouns do not occur in the first person at all, so first and non-first persons are formally distinct.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Personal pronouns have separate forms for singular ('I' and 'you/(s)he') and plural ('we' and 'you/they').
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] These have possessive counterparts: 'my', 'our', 'your/his/her', 'your/their'.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In addition, there are pronoun forms which incorporate numerals from two to five ('the three of us', 'the four of you/them', etc.), though the dual pronouns are slightly idiosyncratic in form *(i.e.,* they have a K rather than 2 handshape, and the wrist nods rather than circles).
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] These numeral-incorporated pronouns have no possessive equivalents.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Also among the personal pronouns are the 'self' forms ('by myself', 'by your/themselves', etc.).
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] These only occur in the singular and plural (there is no numeral incorporation), and are only found as subjects.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] They have derived emphatic and 'characterizing' forms, with modifications used for derivation rather like those for verbal aspect.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The 'characterizing' pronoun is used when describing someone who has just been mentioned.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] It only occurs as a non-first-person singular form.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Finally, there are formal pronouns used for honored guests.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] These occur as singular and plural in the non-first person, but only as singular in the first person.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] ASL is a pro-drop language, which means that pronouns are not used when the referent is obvious from context and is not being emphasized.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Within ASL there is a class of indexical (often called 'directional') verbs.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] These include the signs for 'see', 'pay', 'give', 'show', 'invite', 'help', 'send', 'bite', etc.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] These verbs include an element of motion that indexes one or more referents, either physically present or set up through the referent locus system.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] If there are two loci, the first indicates the subject and the second the object, direct or indirect depending on the verb, reflecting the basic word order of ASL.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, 'give' is a bi-indexical verb based on a flattened M/O handshape.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For 'I give you', the hand moves from myself toward you; for 'you give me', it moves from you to me.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The verb 'to be in pain' (index fingers pointed at each other and alternately approaching and separating) is signed at the location of the pain (head for headache, cheek for toothache, abdomen for stomachache, etc.).
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This is normally done in relation to the signer's own body, regardless of the person feeling the pain, but may take also use the locus system, especially for body parts which are not normally part of the sign space, such as the leg.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-name-sign] There are also spatial verbs such as put-up and put-below, which allow signers to specify where things are or how they moved them around.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-phabet] Like SignFont and Stokoe notation, ASL-phabet is a phonemic script, but it has been simplified to the point where there is some ambiguity, that is, one symbol can represent more than one phonemic element (handshape, location or movement).
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-phabet] For example, whereas SignFont has 25 letters encoding types of movement, and Stokoe notation has 24, ASL-phabet has just 5.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-phabet] This can result in homographs (more than one sign spelled the same way).
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-phabet] All together, ASL-phabet has 22 letters for handshape, 5 for location, and 5 for movement.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-phabet] They are written in that order, left-to-right, with the possibility for several letters of each type, such as two handshape letters for a two-handed sign.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-phabet] Like Stokoe notation (but unlike SignFont), the ASL-phabet does not provide symbols for facial expressions, mouthing, and other aspects of sign language structure, which may make it hard to use for extended text.
[src:alipur-sign-language/asl-phabet] However, it is sufficient to look up ASL words in an ASL–English dictionary.
[src:alipur-sign-language/aslwrite] Its core components are digits, locatives, marks and movements which are written in a fairly rigid order (though in a fairly flexible configuration) from left to right.
[src:alipur-sign-language/aslwrite] The order of the writing is from left to right, top to bottom, with locatives or certain marks often beginning words.
[src:alipur-sign-language/aslwrite] Sentences are ended by the full stop mark ().
[src:alipur-sign-language/aslwrite] Questions in written ASL are denoted by eyebrow marks bounding the question not unlike Spanish's "¿ ?." Question words or wh-questions in ASL can also form the interrogative.
[src:alipur-sign-language/aslwrite] There are in total 105 characters in ASLwrite with 67 digits, five diacritic marks, twelve locatives, sixteen extramanual marks and five movement marks.
[src:alipur-sign-language/aslwrite] Since its creation, it has evolved to include more digits, locatives, movements and marks as well as modify those already present.
[src:alipur-sign-language/aslwrite] si5s, a system built from SignWriting, was first proposed by Robert Arnold in his 2007 Gallaudet thesis *A Proposal of the Written System for ASL*.
[src:alipur-sign-language/aslwrite] The ASLwrite community split from Arnold upon his decision to maintain si5s as a private venture with ASLized after the publication of his and Adrean Clark's book *How to Write American Sign Language*.
[src:alipur-sign-language/aslwrite] Aside from the small, but dedicated, Facebook group of around 470 in July 2023, ASLwrite is rarely used outside such online spaces.
[src:alipur-sign-language/aslwrite] However, one of the most popular online ASL dictionaries, HandSpeak, has begun to incorporate ASLwrite as the primary written component of ASL definitions.
[src:alipur-sign-language/aslwrite] ASLwrite is a somacheirographic system meaning that it represents the body (Greek: σῶμα *sôma* 'body') and hands (Greek: χείρ *kheír* 'hand') and relays phonemic information.
[src:alipur-sign-language/aslwrite] However, it also incorporates logographs (questioning marks) and is featural.
[src:alipur-sign-language/aslwrite] The general principle is to capture a single ASL word per segment, from left to right, registering non-manual feature(s), location(s), handshape(s), movement(s) and general orientation.
[src:alipur-sign-language/aslwrite] It imagines the writer/speaker is looking down at their hands or viewing words from the profile such that words can be made either as if seen from straight-on or from one's profile.
[src:alipur-sign-language/aslwrite] The digibet captures handshape information as well as orientation, movement and some locations.
[src:alipur-sign-language/aslwrite] Locatives are characters that capture location, though handshape diacritics like *edge* do capture some locations such as edge of palm.
[src:alipur-sign-language/aslwrite] Diacritics, such as movements, modify handshapes and can indicate small movements or small orientations.
[src:alipur-sign-language/aslwrite] Movements themselves are fairly flexible in their shapes and orientations, which makes digitising this script difficult.
[src:alipur-sign-language/aslwrite] Frontal or profile locatives – Captures the same location information, just from two perspectives.
[src:alipur-sign-language/aslwrite] An example (seen on the right) is the shoulder locative is either a shoulder frontal locative that is written above or below the handshape(s).
[src:alipur-sign-language/aslwrite] Handshapes – Can be written before or after the locative.
[src:alipur-sign-language/aslwrite] A handshape can be oriented in 360° depending on its location and is written at the end of its movement path if there is one.
[src:alipur-sign-language/aslwrite] Each handshape present is written, and when more than one handshape (of one hand) is written, a movement must be present.
[src:alipur-sign-language/aslwrite] Movements – Larger movements or movements that affect multiple handshapes.
[src:alipur-sign-language/aslwrite] When a handshape changes without overt movement, the handshapes are written left-to-right with a single movement below, similar to an underline.
[src:alipur-sign-language/aslwrite] Non-manual & punctuation marks – These are questioning marks such as *why*, *who*, *how* and *how*.
[src:alipur-sign-language/aslwrite] The digibet is composed of handshapes called digits that are modified by diacritics and movements.
[src:alipur-sign-language/aslwrite] It shares 23 handshapes with ASL's manual alphabet.
[src:alipur-sign-language/aslwrite] Digits are grouped together by features such as +thumb/-thumb or +closed/-closed.
[src:alipur-sign-language/aslwrite] In practise, there are 67 digits in ASLwrite's digibet, though that number is growing as new digits are added representing diverse handshapes.
[src:alipur-sign-language/aslwrite] Moreover, other languages may adopt this system which would add increasingly more digits.
[src:alipur-sign-language/aslwrite] There are five diacritics, of which one is a movement diacritic.
[src:alipur-sign-language/aslwrite] Movements are flexible and thus hard to capture in a digital or non-handwritten fashion.
[src:alipur-sign-language/aslwrite] The movements are diverse and aim to capture the movements of the hands, arms and body.
[src:alipur-sign-language/aslwrite] There are three points – an **endpoint**, a **firmpoint** and a **contactpoint** –, an **orbit mark**, a **steering** and a **crank mark** as well as the movement mark or line.
[src:alipur-sign-language/aslwrite] The movement line follows the path of the hand(s) and can be as clean (e.g., – or | ) or as erratic as possible.
[src:alipur-sign-language/aslwrite] The points denote the end of a handshape's path and the degree to which the motion is made.
[src:alipur-sign-language/aslwrite] A contactpoint denotes an imaginary or in-the-air point with the contactpoint ending at a location and noted as being a firm ending with the firmpoint.
[src:alipur-sign-language/aslwrite] The orbit mark indicates a central "point" around which the handshapes orbit; for orbital paths cut short, one would use a steering mark, and for parallel cranking motions, the crank mark would be used.
[src:alipur-sign-language/aslwrite] The locatives are characters that denote a specific location on or near the signer's body.
[src:alipur-sign-language/aslwrite] They are presented from a face-on and side-view.
[src:alipur-sign-language/aslwrite] The two sub-classifications are **frontal** and **profile locatives**.
[src:alipur-sign-language/aslwrite] Non-manual marks vary quite significantly and can only be placed at the beginning or end of words or phrases.
[src:alipur-sign-language/aslwrite] **Eyebrow marks** are denoted before and after the word(s) in question thus bounding the words that are modified by eyebrow marks.
[src:alipur-sign-language/aslwrite] They are called: **Raised (), Knit, Wan, Slanted** and **Squint**.
[src:alipur-sign-language/aslwrite] Questioning marks exist in ASL as logographs that denote ASL's wh-questions such as WHO or FOR-FOR.
[src:alipur-sign-language/aslwrite] They are placed after a closed word's or phrase's second eyebrow mark and can exist as an entire sentence alone.
[src:alipur-sign-language/aslwrite] Mouth marks are characters that relay what action the mouth is doing.
[src:alipur-sign-language/aslwrite] It is placed inside the first eyebrow mark.
[src:alipur-sign-language/aslwrite] Body movements are non-manual, non-facial features such as **shoulder shift ()** or **head nod**.
[src:alipur-sign-language/aslwrite] They, as well as **nose crinkle ()**, stand alone and can be inserted anywhere, inside and outside of eyebrow-marked phrases.
[src:alipur-sign-language/aslwrite] means *Yes?* in ASL composed of , , and where the raised eyebrow marks at the beginning and the end indicate it is a yes/no question, and the hinge mark () denotes that the S handshape digit () makes a nodding motion.
[src:alipur-sign-language/aslwrite] The circular point at the end is a full stop mark indicating the end of the sentence.
[src:alipur-sign-language/aslwrite] Unlike in English writing, the full stop mark () is employed for all sentences, even questions (as seen here).
[src:alipur-sign-language/aslwrite] Breaks in the sentence, as seen below, are denoted by the shoulder shift mark ().
[src:alipur-sign-language/aslwrite] The text on the right is from Chapters 1:2–4 of the Book of Ruth.
[src:alipur-sign-language/aslwrite] The first quoted text is the verse in English and the second is an ASL gloss.
[src:alipur-sign-language/aslwrite] Due to the complexity of the writing system and its need for flexibility for movements, it means that producing anything in a digital format is difficult.
[src:alipur-sign-language/aslwrite] However, there are efforts to create fonts headed by members of its Facebook group, notably looking at proper font creation and using current keyboard characters such as ' } ' or ' _.
[src:alipur-sign-language/aslwrite] ' to achieve minor forms of communication in ASL over text.
[src:alipur-sign-language/aslwrite] An example phrase is " }_.U- " which means 'thank you' in ASL.
